<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-interchanging-limits"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Interchanging Limits</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Limits do not commute automatically. Even when every object in sight is
      continuous or integrable, taking one limit can destroy the hypotheses
      needed for another. Uniform convergence is the condition that makes many
      familiar limit operations legitimate.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <example xml:id="eg-two-limits-do-not-commute">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define
        <me>
          a_{n,k}=\frac{n}{n+k}.
        </me>
        Then for each fixed <m>n</m>,
        <m>\lim_{k\to\infty} a_{n,k}=0</m>, so
        <me>
          \lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\lim_{k\to\infty} a_{n,k}\right)=0.
        </me>
        But for each fixed <m>k</m>,
        <m>\lim_{n\to\infty} a_{n,k}=1</m>, and therefore
        <me>
          \lim_{k\to\infty}\left(\lim_{n\to\infty} a_{n,k}\right)=1.
        </me>
        So the two iterated limits are different.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-uniform-limit-continuous">
    <title>Continuity of the Uniform Limit</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>x_0 \in S</m>, and suppose
        <m>f_n \colon S \to \R</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m> for every
        <m>n</m>. If <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>S</m>, then
        <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. By uniform convergence, there exists
        <m>N</m> such that
        <me>
          |f_N(x)-f(x)| \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{3}
          \qquad \text{for all } x \in S.
        </me>
        Since <m>f_N</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m>, there exists
        <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
        <me>
          |f_N(x)-f_N(x_0)| \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{3}
          \qquad \text{whenever } x \in S \text{ and } |x-x_0| \lt \delta.
        </me>
        For such <m>x</m>,
        <me>
          |f(x)-f(x_0)|
          \le
          |f(x)-f_N(x)|
          +
          |f_N(x)-f_N(x_0)|
          +
          |f_N(x_0)-f(x_0)|
          \lt
          \varepsilon.
        </me>
        Therefore <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <corollary xml:id="cor-uniform-limit-of-continuous-functions">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </corollary>

  <corollary xml:id="cor-uniform-limit-uniformly-continuous">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>. If each <m>f_n \colon S \to \R</m> is
        uniformly continuous on <m>S</m> and <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on
        <m>S</m>, then <m>f</m> is uniformly continuous on <m>S</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. Choose <m>N</m> such that
        <m>|f(x)-f_N(x)| \lt \varepsilon/3</m> for all <m>x \in S</m>. Since
        <m>f_N</m> is uniformly continuous, there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m>
        such that
        <m>|f_N(x)-f_N(y)| \lt \varepsilon/3</m> whenever
        <m>x,y \in S</m> and <m>|x-y| \lt \delta</m>. For such
        <m>x,y</m>,
        <me>
          |f(x)-f(y)|
          \le
          |f(x)-f_N(x)|+|f_N(x)-f_N(y)|+|f_N(y)-f(y)|
          \lt
          \varepsilon.
        </me>
        Hence <m>f</m> is uniformly continuous on <m>S</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </corollary>

  <example xml:id="eg-pointwise-limit-can-destroy-continuity">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The sequence <m>f_n(x)=x^n</m> on <m>[0,1]</m> converges pointwise to
        the discontinuous limit described in
        <xref ref="eg-pointwise-limit-xn"/>. Thus continuity is not preserved
        by pointwise convergence.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-integral-uniform-limit">
    <title>Integration of the Uniform Limit</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f_n \in R[a,b]</m> for every <m>n</m>, and suppose
        <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>[a,b]</m>. Then <m>f \in R[a,b]</m>,
        and
        <me>
          \int_a^b f
          =
          \lim_{n\to\infty} \int_a^b f_n.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let
        <me>
          c_n=\sup_{x \in [a,b]} |f(x)-f_n(x)|.
        </me>
        Then <m>c_n \to 0</m>. Fix <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, and choose
        <m>n</m> so that <m>c_n \lt \varepsilon/(3(b-a))</m>. Since
        <m>f_n</m> is integrable, the Darboux criterion
        (<xref ref="prop-integrability-criterion-darboux"/>) gives a partition
        <m>P</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> such that
        <me>
          U(P,f_n)-L(P,f_n) \lt \frac{\varepsilon}{3}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        On each subinterval <m>I_j</m> of <m>P</m>, let <m>M_j^n,m_j^n</m> be
        the supremum and infimum of <m>f_n</m>, and let <m>M_j,m_j</m> be the
        corresponding quantities for <m>f</m>. From
        <m>|f-f_n| \le c_n</m> we obtain
        <me>
          M_j \le M_j^n+c_n
          \qquad\text{and}\qquad
          m_j \ge m_j^n-c_n.
        </me>
        Summing over the partition gives
        <me>
          U(P,f)-L(P,f)
          \le
          U(P,f_n)-L(P,f_n)+2c_n(b-a)
          \lt
          \varepsilon.
        </me>
        Therefore <m>f</m> is integrable.
      </p>

      <p>
        Since <m>f-f_n</m> is now integrable, part (4) of
        <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral"/> yields
        <me>
          \left|\int_a^b f-\int_a^b f_n\right|
          =
          \left|\int_a^b (f-f_n)\right|
          \le
          c_n(b-a).
        </me>
        The right-hand side tends to <m>0</m>, so
        <m>\int_a^b f_n \to \int_a^b f</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-spike-functions-integrals">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each <m>n \in \N</m>, define
        <me>
          f_n(x)=
          \begin{cases}
            4n^2x &amp; \text{if } 0 \le x \le \frac{1}{2n},\\
            4n-4n^2x &amp; \text{if } \frac{1}{2n} \lt x \le \frac{1}{n},\\
            0 &amp; \text{if } \frac{1}{n} \lt x \le 1.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Each <m>f_n</m> is continuous on <m>[0,1]</m> and therefore
        integrable. Geometrically, the graph is a triangle of base
        <m>1/n</m> and height <m>2n</m>, so
        <me>
          \int_0^1 f_n = \frac12 \cdot \frac{1}{n} \cdot 2n = 1.
        </me>
        For every fixed <m>x \gt 0</m>, we have <m>f_n(x)=0</m> for all
        sufficiently large <m>n</m>, and clearly <m>f_n(0)=0</m>. Thus
        <m>f_n \to 0</m> pointwise on <m>[0,1]</m>, but
        <me>
          \int_0^1 \lim_{n\to\infty} f_n
          =
          0
          \neq
          1
          =
          \lim_{n\to\infty} \int_0^1 f_n.
        </me>
        So pointwise convergence is not enough to interchange limit and
        integral.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-differentiation-under-uniform-limit">
    <title>Differentiation Under the Limit Sign</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>I \subseteq \R</m> be an open interval, and let
        <m>f_n \in C^1(I)</m> for every <m>n</m>. Suppose there exists a point
        <m>a \in I</m> such that the numerical sequence <m>(f_n(a))</m>
        converges, and suppose that <m>f_n'</m> converges uniformly on every
        compact interval <m>K \subseteq I</m> to a function <m>g</m>. Then
        there exists a differentiable function <m>f \colon I \to \R</m> such
        that <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on every compact interval of
        <m>I</m>, and
        <me>
          f'(x)=g(x)
          \qquad \text{for every } x \in I.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>L=\lim_{n\to\infty} f_n(a)</m>. Fix a compact interval
        <m>K=[u,v] \subseteq I</m>, and set
        <m>\alpha=\min\{a,u\}</m> and <m>\beta=\max\{a,v\}</m>. Then
        <m>[\alpha,\beta] \subseteq I</m>, and by hypothesis
        <m>f_n' \to g</m> uniformly on <m>[\alpha,\beta]</m>. Since each
        <m>f_n'</m> is continuous,
        <xref ref="cor-uniform-limit-of-continuous-functions"/> shows that
        <m>g</m> is continuous on <m>[\alpha,\beta]</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For each <m>x \in K</m>, the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus gives
        <me>
          f_n(x)=f_n(a)+\int_a^x f_n'(t)\,dt.
        </me>
        Define
        <me>
          f(x)=L+\int_a^x g(t)\,dt
          \qquad (x \in I).
        </me>
        Then for <m>x \in K</m>,
        <me>
          |f_n(x)-f(x)|
          \le
          |f_n(a)-L|
          +
          \left|\int_a^x \bigl(f_n'(t)-g(t)\bigr)\,dt\right|
          \le
          |f_n(a)-L| + (\beta-\alpha)\sup_{t \in [\alpha,\beta]} |f_n'(t)-g(t)|.
        </me>
        The right-hand side tends to <m>0</m>, uniformly in <m>x \in K</m>.
        Hence <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>K</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Because <m>g</m> is continuous on every compact interval of <m>I</m>,
        the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus implies that <m>f</m> is
        differentiable on <m>I</m> and that <m>f'(x)=g(x)</m> for every
        <m>x \in I</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-uniform-limit-not-enough-for-derivatives">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Uniform convergence of <m>f_n</m> alone does not justify
        differentiating term by term. Let
        <me>
          f_n(x)=\frac{\sin(nx)}{n}
          \qquad (x \in \R).
        </me>
        Since <m>|f_n(x)| \le 1/n</m>, we have <m>f_n \to 0</m> uniformly on
        <m>\R</m>. But
        <me>
          f_n'(x)=\cos(nx),
        </me>
        and the sequence <m>(\cos(nx))</m> does not even converge pointwise
        on <m>\R</m>; for example, <m>\cos(n\pi)=(-1)^n</m> oscillates.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    Theorems <xref ref="thm-integral-uniform-limit"/> and
    <xref ref="thm-differentiation-under-uniform-limit"/> explain why power
    series can be integrated and differentiated term by term on closed
    subintervals inside their interval of convergence.
  </p>
</section>
